trans-unit.source: _Photo Club Hub_ displays selected photos made by members of photo clubs in a consistent, accessible manner, while minimizing distractions.
trans-unit.target: _Photo Club Hub_ displays selected photos made by members of photo clubs in a consistent, accessible manner, while minimizing distractions.
trans-unit.note: First paragraph in The App section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: This consistency eliminates the need to manually find each club’s website and discover how to navigate its photo galleries. The app doesn’t replace club-, photographer-, or social media sites. Instead, it supports clubs and their members who try to reach out to other clubs, to other photographers, and to a general audience.
trans-unit.target: This consistency eliminates the need to manually find each club’s website and discover how to navigate its photo galleries. The app doesn’t replace club-, photographer-, or social media sites. Instead, it supports clubs and their members who try to reach out to other clubs, to other photographers, and to a general audience.
trans-unit.note: Second paragraph in The App section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: The app aims to strengthen ties between photography clubs and make their members’ photos easily accessible.
trans-unit.target: The app aims to strengthen ties between photography clubs and make their members’ photos easily accessible.
trans-unit.note: Third paragraph in The App section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: The app, originally named _Photo Club Waalre_, was created for a 15-person photo club in the southern Netherlands. The newer name, _Photo Club Hub_, emphasizes the app’s mission to foster connections among various photo clubs.
trans-unit.target: The app, originally named _Photo Club Waalre_, was created for a 15-person photo club in the southern Netherlands. The newer name, _Photo Club Hub_, emphasizes the app’s mission to foster connections among various photo clubs.
trans-unit.note: Fourth paragraph in The App section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: Supporting dozens or even hundreds of clubs necessitates that each club manages its own data, including providing images and maintaining lists of club members. Notably, no software expertise is required to add a club to _Photo Club Hub_.
trans-unit.target: Supporting dozens or even hundreds of clubs necessitates that each club manages its own data, including providing images and maintaining lists of club members. Notably, no software expertise is required to add a club to _Photo Club Hub_.
trans-unit.note: Fifth paragraph in The App section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: Interested in supporting your club? Contact us via [GitHub](https://github.com/vdhamer/Photo-Club-Hub), [Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/vdhamer), or [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/in/vdhamer/). Providing and maintaining club data in a standardized way is all that’s required. The app’s [GitHub site](https://github.com/vdhamer/Photo-Club-Hub) explains this approach in detail. We’re here to help with any questions.
trans-unit.target: Interested in supporting your club? Contact us via [GitHub](https://github.com/vdhamer/Photo-Club-Hub), [Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/vdhamer), or [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/in/vdhamer/). We’re here to help with any questions.

trans-unit.source: Photo clubs play a key role in the app. The central _Portfolios_ screen shows a list of photo clubs.
trans-unit.target: Photo clubs play a key role in the app. The central _Portfolios_ screen shows a list of photo clubs.
trans-unit.note: First paragraph in The Concept on Readme page

trans-unit.source: Each photo club contains a series of member __portfolios__ that hold the actual images. Each portfolio covers the photographer's photos that are associated with that photo club.
trans-unit.target: Each photo club contains a series of member __portfolios__ that hold the actual images. Each portfolio covers the photographer's photos that are associated with that photo club.
trans-unit.note: Second paragraph in The Concept on Readme page

trans-unit.source: A photographer may have multiple portfolios in the app if case the photographer is (or was) associated with more than one photo club.
trans-unit.target: A photographer may have multiple portfolios in the app if case the photographer is (or was) associated with more than one photo club.
trans-unit.note: Third paragraph in The Concept on Readme page

trans-unit.source: Just like a painter, a photographer’s style often changes over the years. Each portfolio should preferably show the images in chronological order, with the latest work first.
trans-unit.target: Just like a painter, a photographer’s style often changes over the years. Each portfolio should preferably show the images in chronological order, with the latest work first.
trans-unit.note: Fourth paragraph in The Concept on Readme page

trans-unit.source: We try to show the portfolios with minimal distraction, just like an exposition at a museum or gallery. Web sites tend to be less suitable for this, because they are cluttered by browser controls (e.g., an address bar or tabs), and generally contain various additional types of information (e.g., club news or schedules).
trans-unit.target: We try to show the portfolios with minimal distraction, just like an exposition at a museum or gallery. trans-unit.source: The app needs information in order to cover your local photo club(s). This involves three so-called __Levels__. A club can stay at any level for a while before proceeding to a next level. See the app’s [README](https://github.com/vdhamer/Photo-Club-Hub/blob/main/.github/README.md) file on GitHub for more details.
trans-unit.target: The app needs information in order to cover your local photo club(s). This involves three so-called __Levels__. A club can stay at any level for a while before proceeding to a next level. See the app’s [README](https://github.com/vdhamer/Photo-Club-Hub/blob/main/.github/README.md) file on GitHub for more details.
trans-unit.note: First paragraph Developers section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: __Level 1__ requires providing the club’s name, location and a few optional links. Once it is on Level 1, the club is listed on the _Clubs and Museums_ screen and shown on maps. If you send us the Level 1 information, we will add it to the app’s online list of clubs. The technically inclined can best submit that information (and any future updates) in the form a [GitHub “pull request”](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BCQHnlnPusY&list=PLRqwX-V7Uu6ZF9C0YMKuns9sLDzK6zoiV): this pretty much automates the integration process and reduces the risk of errors.
trans-unit.target: __Level 1__ requires providing the club’s name, location and a few optional links. Once it is on Level 1, the club is listed on the _Clubs and Museums_ screen and shown on maps. If you send us the Level 1 information, we will add it to the app’s online list of clubs. The technically inclined can best submit that information (and any future updates) in the form a [GitHub “pull request”](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BCQHnlnPusY&list=PLRqwX-V7Uu6ZF9C0YMKuns9sLDzK6zoiV): this pretty much automates the integration process and reduces the risk of errors.
trans-unit.note: Second paragraph Developers section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: __Level 2__ requires providing a list of the names of current (and optionally former) club members as a text file with a specific format. This file can be stored anywhere as long as it can be fetched using a web address (URL). For example, you can store it in the _Media_ section of your club’s _Wordpress_ web site. At Level 2, the membership lists show up on the _Portfolios_ screen. _Fotogroep Anders_ (NL) shows what a Level 2 club looks like in the user interface.
trans-unit.target: __Level 2__ requires providing a list of the names of current (and optionally former) club members as a text file with a specific format. This file can be stored anywhere as long as it can be fetched using a web address (URL). For example, you can store it in the _Media_ section of your club’s _Wordpress_ web site. At Level 2, the membership lists show up on the _Portfolios_ screen. _Fotogroep Anders_ (NL) shows what a Level 2 club looks like in the user interface.
trans-unit.note: Third paragraph Developers section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: Clubs at __Level 3__ also provide links to the online images in member portfolios. _Fotogroep de Gender_ (NL) is an example of a Level 3 club: you can view their portfolios via the _Portfolios_ screen. Because a club with dozens of members may want to show hundreds of images, we have a way to automatically create portfolios from _Lightroom_ collections (step-by-step instructions for this will be made available)
trans-unit.target: Clubs at __Level 3__ also provide links to the online images in member portfolios. _Fotogroep de Gender_ (NL) is an example of a Level 3 club: you can view their portfolios via the _Portfolios_ screen. Because a club with dozens of members may want to show hundreds of images, we have a way to automatically create portfolios from _Lightroom_ collections (step-by-step instructions for this will be made available)
trans-unit.note: Fourth paragraph Developers section of Readme page

trans-unit.source: Help with onboarding of additional clubs is essential. But there are more ways in which you can help out. Examples of __non-technical help__ include testing, writing a review for Apple’s App Store, creating step-by-step user instructions, and coming up with improvement ideas. Last, and certainly not least, actual _software development_ support will help speed up app enhancements, produce fresh ideas and ensure app continuity. Example contributions include code improvement of all sorts (via [GitHub](https://github.com/vdhamer/Photo-Club-Hub)), hunting down bugs, and contributing to discussions on functionality, implementation and interfaces.
